<rss xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0"><channel><title>Daily Dot</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/</link><description>Daily Dot Article</description><atom:link href="http://www.dailydot.com/feed/article/27384/" rel="self"></atom:link><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Fri, 22 Feb 2013 16:32:51 +0000</lastBuildDate><item><title>Forget strippers: Spend your Bitcoins on the Internet Archive</title><link>http://www.dailydot.com/business/bitcoins-internet-archive-drugs-strippers/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src='//cdn0.dailydot.com/cache/c5/ae/c5aed862f450db58ef27c13a33540e8d.jpg'&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;
	It&amp;#39;s been a good week for Bitcoin. Earlier today, the online digital currency &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/business/bitcoin-30-milestone-exchange-rate-usd/"&gt;hit $30 per coin&lt;/a&gt; for the first time since 2011. Yesterday, it got the endorsement of another high-profile online group.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Fans of the &lt;a href="http://archive.org/"&gt;Internet Archive&lt;/a&gt; can now donate to the digital library in Bitcoins, the nonprofit announced Thursday. In fact, some employees have actually requested to be paid in Bitcoins, &lt;a href="http://brewster.kahle.org/2013/02/20/bitcoin-is-the-local-currency-of-the-internet/"&gt;according&lt;/a&gt; to the Archive&amp;#39;s press release.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The Internet Archive hosts 10 petabytes (or 10,000,000,000,000,000 bytes) of digital cultural material, from movies to music to historical snapshots of the entire Internet (via the Archive&amp;#39;s popular Wayback Machine tool). It has 200 employees.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The Archive&amp;#39;s founder &lt;a href="http://blog.archive.org/2013/02/21/employees-to-be-paid-in-bitcoin-please-donate/"&gt;expressed&lt;/a&gt; his admiration for Bitcoins on Wednesday. Brewster Kahle called the online currency the &amp;quot;local currency&amp;quot; of the Internet.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		There are local currencies like &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ithaca_Hours"&gt;Ithaca Hours&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href="https://bernalbucks.org/"&gt;Bernal Bucks&lt;/a&gt; that facilitate trading within a community. Bitcoins are kind of like that. [They are] for those of the Internet.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;quot;I feel like I am part of a club, and it is fun,&amp;quot; he added.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Bitcoins are already accepted at &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/news/buy-reddit-gold-bitcoins/"&gt;Reddit&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="http://en.blog.wordpress.com/2012/11/15/pay-another-way-bitcoin/"&gt;Wordpress&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/society/girls-gone-bitcoin-strippers-interview/"&gt;stripping forums&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/news/silk-road-online-drug-marketplace-dealer-guilty/"&gt;narcotic wholesale shops&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="http://www.dailydot.com/business/bitcoin-online-gambling-us-poker-sites/"&gt;online casinos&lt;/a&gt; around the world.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Philanthropic Bitcoin hoarders can dump their digital riches here, at the Archive&amp;#39;s Bitcoin address: 17gN64BPHtxi4mEM3qWrxdwhieUvRq8R2r.&lt;/p&gt;
